At least 14 per cent of women said ‘abortion should be legal in any circumstances’; while 11 per cent said ‘abortion should be legal in the early stages of the pregnancy only’; 2 per cent said ‘abortion should be legal in case of rape’; and 4 percent said ‘abortion should be legal when the physical or mental wellbeing of the woman is at risk’.6 Although abortion is restricted and illegal in many countries, health professionals routinely provide information about locations of safe, legal abortion services to women who request information about available choices. Our finding is consistent with those of United Nations studies which found that women sought abortions, and that public health care providers were key mediators in the provision of information about safe services.
Directors of public health facilities report that, although it is their policy not to refer, they do refer women for abortions and provide information to those women who request it from providers at places where abortions are unavailable.
Some directors of public health facilities tell us they refer pregnant women to another province, such as Kamiti, to have abortions. These directors do not treat the matter formally or share the information publicly arguing it is not their place to be involved in the matter for fear that it would put them and their centres at risk with local political leadership if they were to advert to the scheme.
